04366nam a22005415i 9780226334219DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263342197 a10.7208/97802263342192doi  a(DE-B1597)525005  a(OCoLC)945663128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aF128.68.S64 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a700.974709042231 aShkuda, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lofts of SoHo :bGentrification, Art, and Industry in New York, 1950-1980 /cAaron Shkuda. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b23 halftones, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Art, Artists, and Gentrifi cation -- t1. The Wastelands of New York -- t2. Making the Artist Loft -- t3. Gray Areas and Industrial Slums: The Lower Manhattan Expressway -- t4. Artist Organizations, Political Advocacy, and the Creation of a Residential SoHo -- t5. Moving Art Downtown -- t6. Real Estate and SoHo Politics: Loft Promotion and Historic Preservation in Lower Manhattan -- t7. The Embourgeoisement of SoHo -- t8. The Spread of Loft Living: Real Estate Development and Tenant Conflict in SoHo and Beyond -- t9. Making New York a Loft Living City -- tConclusion. Contemporary SoHo and the Neighborhood's Signifi cance -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican cities entered a new phase when, beginning in the 1950s, artists and developers looked upon a decaying industrial zone in Lower Manhattan and saw, not blight, but opportunity: cheap rents, lax regulation, and wide open spaces. Thus, SoHo was born. From 1960 to 1980, residents transformed the industrial neighborhood into an artist district, creating the conditions under which it evolved into an upper-income, gentrified area. Introducing the idea-still potent in city planning today-that art could be harnessed to drive municipal prosperity, SoHo was the forerunner of gentrified districts in cities nationwide, spawning the notion of the creative class. In The Lofts of SoHo, Aaron Shkuda studies the transition of the district from industrial space to artists' enclave to affluent residential area, focusing on the legacy of urban renewal in and around SoHo and the growth of artist-led redevelopment. Shkuda explores conflicts between residents and property owners and analyzes the city's embrace of the once-illegal loft conversion as an urban development strategy. As Shkuda explains, artists eventually lost control of SoHo's development, but over several decades they nonetheless forced scholars, policymakers, and the general public to take them seriously as critical actors in the twentieth-century American city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226334219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226334219.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles